{"action": "input", "code": "def find_rectangle(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[int, int, int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Finds the rectangle with the same boundary color in the input_grid, and all pixels except for the boundary are black in color.\n\n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array representing the input grid.\n\n    Returns:\n    A tuple of four integers representing the coordinates of the rectangle in the input_grid in the format (x1, y1, x2, y2).\n    \"\"\"\n    m = _find_boundary_color(input_grid)\n    out = _find_rectangle(input_grid, m)\n    return out\ndef main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    m = find_rectangle(input_grid)\n    out = replace_boundary_with_color(input_grid, m)\n    return out\ndef replace_boundary_with_color(input_grid: np.ndarray, boundary: Tuple[int, int, int, int], color: int) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    Finds the matrix with black pixels, and its shape is the same as the non-boundary part of boundary. Replaces its boundary with the given color.\n\n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array representing the input grid.\n    boundary: A tuple of four integers representing the coordinates of the rectangle in the input_grid in the format (x1, y1, x2, y2).\n    color: An integer representing the color to replace the boundary with.\n\n    Returns:\n    A numpy array representing the input grid with the boundary replaced with the given color.\n    \"\"\"\n    x1, y1, x2, y2 = boundary\n    matrix = input_grid[x1 + 1:x2, y1 + 1:y2]\n    matrix[:, 0] = color\n    matrix[:, -1] = color\n    matrix[0, :] = color\n    matrix[-1, :] = color\n    input_grid[x1 + 1:x2, y1 + 1:y2] = matrix\n    return input_grid", "user_code": "def main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n  m = `There is a rectangle with the same boundary color in the input_grid, and all pixels except for the boundary are black in color, find and return it`(input_grid)\n  out = `There is a matrix with black pixels, and its shape is the same as the non-boundary part of m. Find it and replace its boundary with the boundary color of m`(input_grid, m)\n  return out\n  ", "gpt_code": "def find_rectangle(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[int, int, int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Finds the rectangle with the same boundary color in the input_grid, and all pixels except for the boundary are black in color.\n\n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array representing the input grid.\n\n    Returns:\n    A tuple of four integers representing the coordinates of the rectangle in the input_grid in the format (x1, y1, x2, y2).\n    \"\"\"\n    m = _find_boundary_color(input_grid)\n    out = _find_rectangle(input_grid, m)\n    return out\ndef replace_boundary_with_color(input_grid: np.ndarray, boundary: Tuple[int, int, int, int], color: int) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    Finds the matrix with black pixels, and its shape is the same as the non-boundary part of boundary. Replaces its boundary with the given color.\n\n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array representing the input grid.\n    boundary: A tuple of four integers representing the coordinates of the rectangle in the input_grid in the format (x1, y1, x2, y2).\n    color: An integer representing the color to replace the boundary with.\n\n    Returns:\n    A numpy array representing the input grid with the boundary replaced with the given color.\n    \"\"\"\n    x1, y1, x2, y2 = boundary\n    matrix = input_grid[x1 + 1:x2, y1 + 1:y2]\n    matrix[:, 0] = color\n    matrix[:, -1] = color\n    matrix[0, :] = color\n    matrix[-1, :] = color\n    input_grid[x1 + 1:x2, y1 + 1:y2] = matrix\n    return input_grid", "holes": {"find_rectangle": "There is a rectangle with the same boundary color in the input_grid, and all pixels except for the boundary are black in color, find and return it", "replace_boundary_with_color": "There is a matrix with black pixels, and its shape is the same as the non-boundary part of m. Find it and replace its boundary with the boundary color of m"}}
